Click the link in bio to read more about The Unplug Collective.

node.text:
Who needs a laugh 🙋 In our latest Quick Questions episode, WNBA greats Sylvia Fowles (@sylvia_fowles) and A’ja Wilson (@aja22wilson) dish out laughs over their first bra, the most surprising thing about themselves, and what they admire most about each other. 
 
Shot at Nike Headquarters, January 2020

Shot at Nike Headquarters, January 2020 *

node.text:
“I’m telling my own story my own way.” ⠀ ⠀

@katelyn_ohashi, UCLA NCAA Gymnastics Champion, poet and activist, is gearing up to run half marathon, LA 13.1. As she embarks on an exciting new phase of life post-undergrad and post-retirement, Katelyn shows that when we believe we are capable, we have the power to redefine our narratives.

node.text: Fashion designer / creative director / extremely cool human @yoon_ambush is all about transforming the mundane into something ✨special✨. And when she’s featured in her own campaigns (with some help from @theestallion, which 👌), designing her latest Nike x @ambush_official apparel collab, AND serving as Dior Men’s Jewelry Director 🤯, her inspiration can come from anywhere. Like motorcycle culture meets anime meets Tokyo’s neon lights. Aka yes pls.

node.text:
“Growing up as an only child, I made all my own moves to get to where I am today. I know the struggle of pulling yourself up. That’s why it’s most important to me to be an example for the kids in my South Central community. Through the way I show up in the world, my hope is that they can see what’s possible.”
 
Greatness can come from anywhere. Like an old Eastbay catalog featuring row after row of pristine cheer shoes. Or at least, that’s how it worked for Tamia Mathis – stylist, former cheerleader (obv), and LA icon. Her catalog collection is what sparked her love of sneakers, which led to her creating a fashion club in high school, which led to her hustling up styling gigs by 19. It wasn’t always easy, but she made it happen…and now she’s hoping to help others find their path to greatness, too.

node.text:
“I hope that I inspire kids to find their dreams the way I found mine. We only live once—I want everyone to choose their own path in life and do everything to the fullest.” 

Thailand’s Taekwondo star @panipak2540 —aka Tennis—always knew sport would be a big part of her life (with siblings named Bowling and Baseball, it was kind of a given 💁‍♀️). Taekwondo taught her to fight to the end, and always get back up. Now, she’s teaching it to the next generation to give them the tools they need to follow their own dreams. 🔥✨
#NewHeroes

node.text:
“I am always present in my style. Anything that moves me or doesn’t move me, a plant, a car, whatever — it all could inspire my style.” - @lizethselene 

Lizeth Selene — better known simply as Selene when she’s making music — draws ✨energy✨ from moving through her environment and connecting with everything around her. She snapped some pics around her neighborhood in Mexico City 🇲🇽 to show how the Blazer Low Platform brings flavor to any fit. Head to Stories to see how she styles it ✔️✔️✔️

node.text:
When @runwithzha – runner, creative, and ✨ THE ✨ most serene new mom – got pregnant, she knew her workouts would have to change. But years spent training for marathons taught her a thing or two about setting goals—so she was able to see that what felt like a step back would actually be hugely helpful in the long run. ALL PUNS VERY MUCH INTENDED.

“During my second trimester, the runs got a little slower and the movement got a little less, but my body was going through a transition—I had to listen to it. And movement now is even more exciting than it was before I gave birth because I've had a few weeks not being able to do it. I run with more purpose.”

node.text:
“If I can introduce all these young female athletes to all these different shapes, sizes, and colors of athletes, someone is bound to find themselves in one.”

Michelle Carter started her career in the shot put by hearing a lie: that winning and being great in the sport had to be ugly. Her inspiration to bring glam to the shot put ring is part of the New Resilience. As Michelle made her way up the ranks of the shot put worldwide, she has also sought to inspire the next generation. Through her “You Throw Girl” camp, Michelle hopes that young girls can find athletic role models who look like them. 

🎥: @rashadfloyd 
📷: @flongala 
📷: @54ghosts

node.text:
“I want trans people to be seen for all that they are, beyond just being trans. There is so much more to us.”
@gia.parr is a student/model/advocate/athlete—aka a full human being 💅🏼And backed by her positive peers 🙌 and field hockey teammates 🏑, Gia has a supportive team that sees that full self. Now, she’s looking toward the future—by sharing her story, and her truth.
 
Director: @emily_mcdon 
DP: @bhoste
Photographer: @mylesloftin 
Stylist: @shibonleigh 
Hair & Make Up: Josie Torres

node.text:
Our stylist @kattypaldos knows that when it comes to personal style, there is no one size fits all. “The Waffle is sport at its core. But you don’t need to be an elite athlete to wear a shoe like this,” she says. “We don’t belong in categories. We dress, we pick, we choose. What we’re seeing is a cross pollination of genres, across music, art, and style. By stepping out of expectations, we’re creating new spaces and expanding our possibilities.”
 
Introducing the Nike Waffle One – built for those who break the mold.

node.text:
MAKE WAY for @candicebrathwaite – best-selling author, journalist, TV presenter, founder of @makemotherhooddiverse, AND weekend runner, nbd – as she holds space for other Black Mothers on the latest ep of the @blackmumsupfront podcast. 💪💯
 
The group talks about the importance of Black narratives being told, Black maternal death rates in the UK, and Candice’s new book, Sista Sister — essays on the things she wishes she’d been told when she was younger (and that’s just in the first 5 minutes 🤯). Check the link in bio to hear the whole convo☝

⚠️ Trigger warning, this episode contains content that some listeners may find upsetting.
